<div id="review_3410968205" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3410968205" />
    <a title="Luís" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/117399210-lu-s"><img alt="Luís" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1620236159p2/117399210.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3410968205?book_show_action=true">Jun 25, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Luís" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Luís" href="/user/show/117399210-lu-s">Luís</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9789897220715" href="/book/show/17257384-o-aleph">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/117399210-lu-s?shelf=classics">classics</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/117399210-lu-s?shelf=fantasy">fantasy</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/117399210-lu-s?shelf=magical-realism">magical-realism</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/117399210-lu-s?shelf=favorites">favorites</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/117399210-lu-s?shelf=latin-american">latin-american</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3410968205" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9232068001102948109">It is always a pleasure for me to read Borges. I read with delight each of the short stories in this collection.<br/>Borges, always faithful to his style and his magic transports his reader to extraordinary places to discover fabulous things and stories. He leads it with his Borgesian cunning, multiplying references and names. He doesn&apos;t tell, Borges builds labyrinths.<br/><br/>From the new metaphysics (if you will) to the new detective, to the philosophical but also mythological tale, we lose ourselves to fin</span>
  <span id="freeText9232068001102948109" style="display:none">It is always a pleasure for me to read Borges. I read with delight each of the short stories in this collection.<br />Borges, always faithful to his style and his magic transports his reader to extraordinary places to discover fabulous things and stories. He leads it with his Borgesian cunning, multiplying references and names. He doesn't tell, Borges builds labyrinths.<br /><br />From the new metaphysics (if you will) to the new detective, to the philosophical but also mythological tale, we lose ourselves to find ourselves, as Claude Mauriac said, more intelligent.<br /><br />For Borges, who has always read a lot, everything steeped in universal literature; each act explained by research and finds an echo in it, each being has a literary or mythological double. In Borges' short stories nothing is written at random; each sentence has its importance in the construction. Thirsty for knowledge and discovery, Borges pursues his search for the absolute, the ultimate, the whole which brings together all universe's experience, all the places, all the objects, of the sentence which sums up the entire mystery of existence. For him; the world is a real unfathomable labyrinth, which keeps its secrets, and every man represents all men in a game of symmetries.<br /><br />One of the short stories, "The Abode of Asterion" curiously reminded me of a chapter in "Praise of the Stepmother" by Vargas Llosa where the narrator is a monster which is "Head I" painted by Francis Bacon. The two characters are monsters inspired by paintings and mythology, are naive, sympathetic and pathetic.</span>
  <a data-text-id="9232068001102948109" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


